## SafetyChain Flow Policy

This policy applies to every agent in the SafetyChain city. It governs how
the mayor dispatches work, how polecats pick up work, and how humans are
notified when their input is needed.

### Entry-mode detection (mayor only)

When the human asks the mayor to plan something, **delegate to the
Quartermaster pool** — do NOT run `mol-sc-idea-to-plan` inline in Mayor's
session. Mayor has `max_active_sessions=1` and the plan gate waits up to
24h on the human's approval mail; running planning inline blocks Mayor from
all other coordination work.

Inspect the request, then sling to `hq/quartermaster`:

- Contains a Linear issue ID matching `SAF-\d+` → **Linear path**. Extract
  the ID. Call `linear-server get_issue` to pull title + description;
  synthesize problem + context strings; call `linear-server save_issue`
  with `state="In Progress"`. Then:
  ```bash
  gc sling hq/quartermaster mol-sc-idea-to-plan --formula \
    --var linear_id=SAF-XX \
    --var problem="<synthesized problem>" \
    --var context="<synthesized context>"
  ```
- No Linear ID → **free-text path**. Sling with problem + context only:
  ```bash
  gc sling hq/quartermaster mol-sc-idea-to-plan --formula \
    --var problem="<exact user text>" \
    --var context="<supplementary info>"
  ```
  Do not invent or guess a Linear ID.

Reply to the human with the new Quartermaster session ID so they know where to
send approval mail. Then stop — do not wait for the plan to finish. A
single Quartermaster pool can run up to 3 plans in parallel; check
`gc session list` before reporting a "no slot available" state.

Both paths produce the same downstream artifact (reviewed plan plus a
convoy of beads). Only the Linear path triggers MCP state transitions and
stamps `External:` on the root bead.

### Polecat variant selection (mayor picks at sling time)

Three variants exist in every rig, bound to Claude provider presets. They
live in the `polecats` pack (`<city>/packs/polecats/`) which is imported
per-rig via `[rigs.imports.polecats]` in city.toml, so the sling target
format is `<rig>/polecats.<variant>`:

| Variant | Provider preset | When to use |
|---|---|---|
| `polecats.sonnet` | claude-sonnet, effort=medium | default implementation; parallel review legs; plain mechanical work once a plan is good |
| `polecats.opus-high` | claude-opus-high, effort=high | implementation that mentions architecture, migration, cross-cutting, new subsystem, hard debug, security-sensitive, data model |
| `polecats.opus-max-1m` | claude-opus-max, effort=max, model=opus[1m] | implementation slices that need 1M context — large refactors, cross-subsystem rewrites, data-model migrations where the whole design doc + surrounding code must be in scope |

Default to sonnet. Escalate to opus-high only when bead text shows
complexity signals. Reserve opus-max-1m for implementation work that
genuinely needs the full 1M window; everyday "complex" work is opus-high.

**Planning does not run on any polecat variant.** It runs on the
city-scoped `hq/quartermaster` agent (also `claude-opus-max`), which
is what Mayor delegates to on every plan request — see "Entry-mode
detection" above. Polecats implement slices; Quartermaster plans them.

### Agent-tier stamping (Quartermaster, during `create-beads`)

When `mol-sc-idea-to-plan` reaches the `create-beads` step, the
Quartermaster must stamp `metadata.agent_tier` + a `tier:<x>` label on
every task bead. This is a deliberate per-slice decision made with the
design doc in context — the downstream sling formula honors it instead
of re-deriving from bead text.

| Tier | Use for |
|---|---|
| `sonnet` | Default. Vertical slice touches a bounded area, straightforward implementation, clear acceptance criteria. |
| `opus-high` | Design judgment required, cross-cutting, non-trivial tests, security-sensitive, or the design doc flagged the slice as complex. |
| `opus-max-1m` | Needs the full design doc + surrounding code in context: large refactors, novel subsystems, data-model migrations, anything that wouldn't fit in a normal context window. |

Stamp each task bead:

```bash
bd update "$TASK_ID" --set-metadata agent_tier=$TIER
bd label add "$TASK_ID" "tier:$TIER"
```

Default to `sonnet`. Only escalate when you can name the specific
complexity signal from the design doc that forces it.

### Convoy dispatch procedure (mayor)

When dispatching an approved convoy for implementation, walk the children
and sling each individually. For larger convoys or resumable dispatch,
prefer `mol-sc-sling-convoy` (a formula that does the walk for you). For
one-off ad-hoc slings, do it inline:

```bash
CONVOY="<convoy-id>"
RIG="$GC_RIG"                       # or an explicit rig

for BEAD in $(bd list --parent "$CONVOY" --status=open --json | jq -r '.[].id'); do
  # 1. Inspect the bead
  META=$(bd show "$BEAD" --json)
  TEXT=$(printf '%s' "$META" | jq -r '.[0] | "\(.title)\n\(.description // "")"')

  # 2. Classify complexity
  VARIANT="polecats.sonnet"         # default
  TRIVIAL="false"
  # - trivial heuristic: single-file edit, typo, version bump, config/string rename,
  #   comment-only, trivial doc. If yes: TRIVIAL=true (polecat skips ralph).
  # - opus-high heuristic: architecture, migration, cross-cutting, new subsystem,
  #   hard debug, security-sensitive, data model. If yes: VARIANT=polecats.opus-high.

  # 3. Sling with formula + trivial metadata
  gc sling "$RIG/$VARIANT" "$BEAD" \
    --on mol-polecat-work-monorepo \
    --meta trivial="$TRIVIAL"
  # Use mol-polecat-work-monorepo-tdd if the bead calls for tests-first.
done
```

Polecats run in parallel up to pool max. Do not wait between slings.

### Ralph-loop default (polecat behavior)

During the `implement` step, polecats must use the `ralph-loop:ralph-loop`
plugin skill to drive non-trivial work.

A bead is **trivial** (skip ralph) when any of:

- `metadata.trivial=true` was set at sling time by the mayor
- bead title/description clearly describes: single-file edit, typo fix,
  dependency version bump, config or string rename, comment-only change,
  trivial doc edit

When uncertain, default to ralph — the cost of unnecessary ralph is small;
the cost of a half-baked change spanning multiple files is large.

If the mayor did not set `metadata.trivial` but the polecat judges the
work trivial on inspection, the polecat may skip ralph on its own. Log
the decision in bead notes either way.

### Human notification and async reply

Any workflow step that pauses waiting for the human must call:

```bash
assets/scripts/sc-notify-human.sh "<subject>" "<body>"
```

Do **not** rely on `gc mail send human --notify` alone — the `--notify`
flag is a no-op for the `human` recipient in this version of Gas City
(see gastown `examples/gastown/FUTURE.md`). The helper fans out to macOS
notifications, an optional outbound webhook (`$SC_NOTIFY_WEBHOOK`), a
tmux bell when attached, and an inbox mail for audit trail.

The reply channel is **mail**, not live conversation. The coordinator
polecat runs in its own tmux session; the human is usually not attached.
Include in every notification body the exact reply command:

```
gc mail send <COORDINATOR_SESSION> -s "<gate-name>" -m "y|request-changes: ...|abort"
```

The paused polecat polls its own inbox (60 s cadence) for mail with the
expected subject, then acts on the body. Never block on live-conversation
input that requires the human to be attached.

### Standing rules

- **Target branch**: always `boylec/develop` for SafetyChain. Enforced by
  the `GC_TARGET_BRANCH` env var on polecat variants and refinery. Verify
  with `echo $GC_TARGET_BRANCH` before pushing.
- **Commit suffix**: if the bead has `External: linear-SAF-XX`, commit
  messages end with `[SAF-XX]`. Otherwise end with `[<bead-id>]`. Never
  use `Closes SAF-XX` or `Fixes SAF-XX` in PR bodies — Gas City lifecycle
  owns Linear transitions, not GitHub auto-close.
- **Bead linkage to Linear**: when `mol-sc-idea-to-plan` creates the
  convoy, it stamps `metadata.linear_id` and `--external-ref linear-SAF-XX`
  on the convoy and every child bead. Polecats read these and rely on the
  existing `linear-transitions` fragment for per-bead state transitions.
